EDA is done in three levels:

1 Univariate → single column
2 Bivariate → two columns
3 Multivariate → full dataset

Numerical → Numerical
Categorical → Categorical
Numerical ↔ Categorical

1. First step: Identify column types

num_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['int64','float64']).columns
cat_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['object','category']).columns

2 EDA for Numerical Columns

(A) Distribution analysis

Histogram
df[num_cols].hist(figsize=(12,8))

You learn:
normal distribution
skewness
spread of data

(b) Outlier detection

Boxplot
sns.boxplot(data=df[num_cols])

This shows:
extreme values
quartiles

(c) Relationship between numerical features

Correlation heatmap
sns.heatmap(df[num_cols].corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm')

This reveals:
multicollinearity
strong predictors
median

3. EDA for Categorical Columns

(a) Frequency analysis

Countplot
for col in cat_cols:
    sns.countplot(x=col, data=df)
    plt.show()

You learn:
class imbalance
dominant categories

(b) Percentage distribution

df['gender'].value_counts(normalize=True)
Useful in classification problems to detect imbalance.

4. Numerical vs Categorical (Most Important Part)

(a) Boxplot grouped by category

Example: salary by gender
sns.boxplot(x='gender', y='salary', data=df)

You learn:
how numerical values change across categories
group comparison


(b) Violin plot (better than boxplot)

sns.violinplot(x='gender', y='salary', data=df)
Shows:
full distribution for each category


(c) Barplot with mean values

sns.barplot(x='department', y='salary', data=df
This shows:
average value per category

5. Categorical vs Categorical

(a) Crosstab (table)

pd.crosstab(df['gender'], df['department'])

(b) Heatmap of crosstab

sns.heatmap(pd.crosstab(df['gender'], df['department']), annot=True)

This reveals:
category relationships
patterns like bias or imbalance

6. Multivariate visualization (Full dataset)

Pairplot with hue
This works only when numerical + categorical target exists.

sns.pairplot(df, hue='target')

You learn:
class separation
interactions between many variables

7. Missing values by type

Numerical missing pattern
sns.heatmap(df[num_cols].isnull())

Categorical missing pattern
sns.heatmap(df[cat_cols].isnull())

8. Feature importance after encoding categorical columns

Categorical columns must be encoded before model training:
df_encoded = pd.get_dummies(df, drop_first=True)

model.fit(X, y)
plt.barh(X.columns, model.feature_importances_)
